Parents and Caregivers:
The Addison Central School District's priority is your student’s health and safety, while maximizing in-person instruction. Our goal is to have ALL students return to in-person learning in September. As we are working through our planning process, we value your voice. We need your input and support. PLEASE CHECK YOUR EMAIL FOR AN IMPORTANT MESSAGE WITH A LINK TO A PARENT SURVEY FROM THE ACSD.

Below is the ACSD Re-opening Framework that we are following as we develop plans. We are awaiting further guidance from Governor Cuomo's office, which we expect to receive during the first week of August. We will share additional information when we have this guidance and plans are finalized.

During this time of celebrations, we've been asked to remind everyone of the Steuben County Social Host Law, which addresses providing children under the age of 21 with a place to use alcohol and drugs.
In addition, providing such items to minors is a separate crime that is punishable by a fine of up to $1,000 and up to one year in jail.
Please review the memo below from Steuben County District Attorney Brooks Baker.

Addison High School
June 12 at 10:57 AM ·

The Addison High School is proud to announce that Jeremy Wilson is one of the county-wide recipients of the The Jack Lisi Youth Award. This award program targets an often overlooked population and offers incentives to youth who have shown interest and ambition towards academic or employment goals. Award recipients are selected by partner school committees to receive awards and incentives, dependent upon information expressed on the recommendation forms. Jack Lisi believed that what was needed was someone to care, show support, give assistance, and guidance in order for youngsters to become contributing members of society. Congratulations to Jeremy Wilson!

ATTENTION ADDISON COMMUNITY MEMBERS:
The Addison School District is offering a special opportunity to our community on May 15. Phase III construction and renovation in the High School auditorium has provided community members a chance to preserve a piece of the district's history in their own homes! There are approximately 35 sets (three-five chairs per set/one set per person/pickup) of high school auditorium seats that will be available free of charge. The set includes an aisle seat with "AHS" engraved on the side. Here is what you need to know:

· Who: Addison Community Members/Alumni
· When: May 15, 9:00 am-3:00 pm
· Where: Annex Facility, 7787 State Route 417
· This is by first come, first served basis
· Chair transportation is YOUR responsibility—delivery is not available
· A staff member will be present to assist community members
· Please follow social distancing guidelines and stay in your vehicle
· A signature that releases the school district from any liability regarding any future use of these chairs will be required

post_text:
If you or someone you know has been affected financially by COVID-19, WIC may be able to help. WIC (The Special Supplemental Nutrition Program for Women, Infants, and Children) provides pregnant women, new and breastfeeding moms and children under age 5 with healthy food, breastfeeding support, nutrition advice and referrals to other services.

Steuben and Yates County residents are encouraged to reach out for more information or to find out if they may be eligible. Contact WIC Help Specialist Amanda by text/call at (607)-377-4313 or via email at DowdleA@proactioninc.org.
You also can visit their website at www.proactioninc.org for more on all programs and services available at ProAction of Steuben and Yates, Inc.

During a press conference today, Governor Cuomo announced that all NYS school districts will remain closed for in-school instruction for the remainder of the 2019-20 academic year.

However, at-home learning and assignments will continue through the end of the school year.

The Governor will announce a decision regarding the operation of summer school by the end of May. Meal plans and childcare programs are slated to continue.

We will continue to share updated information as it becomes available.

During the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2-1-1 HELPLINE serves as a lifeline for those in our region in need of human services intervention.

You can call or text 2-1-1 to speak with a community resource specialist who can help find services and resources that are available to you.

2-1-1 is available 24/7 across all of New York and has the most up-to-date resources on non-profit and government programs currently available to support our community.

UPDATE FROM ADDISON CENTRAL SCHOOL DISTRICT

Curbside meal pick-up at the High School, Valley and the Woodhull Town Hall continues, but the schedule is revised for this week (April 6-10). There will be NO meal pick-up on Friday, April 10. Pick-ups on Wednesday, April 8 will include food for Wednesday, Thursday and Friday. The Monday, Wednesday and Friday schedule will resume on April 13.

As per Governor Andrew Cuomo's recent announcement, the school closure mandate has been extended until April 29.

The New York State Board of Regents announced that Regents examinations for this June will be cancelled. We will provide further details on this as they are available.

The Addison Central School District and Armstrong Telephone have partnered to offer WiFi access sites to families during school closings. These are drive-up sites that can be accessed in the parking lot at each location; parents and children are asked to remain in their vehicles while using the internet. These locations will be available beginning on Monday, March 23:

• Addison Community Center, 13 Community Drive, Addison
• Woodhull Town Hall, 1585 Academy Street, Woodhull

In addition to the Armstrong hot spots, families are invited to connect to guest internet access at all Addison school parking lots, available immediately. To connect, select the “ACSD Guest” WiFi network and use the following credentials:
Username: guest
Password: Addison3#

If students are experiencing any issues with their school-issued computers, parents can call 607-359-2241 for technology support.

Enhanced referrals will include facilitating the process of finding an available slot so that parents in these crucial service professions have less legwork to do. shared_text:
Tuscarora Elementary School
February 24 at 11:41 AM ·

Second graders recently shared personal narratives about what they excel at. This year, the second grade team decided to give the students have a choice in how they wanted to share their story. Some students choose to build a pool with Legos, create a movie, bring in baked goods they made, create a PowerPoint presentation, make a poster or demonstrate to their peers what they excel at. Mrs. Hamilton's students learned about gymnastics, yoga, soccer, baseball, wrestling, cooking, fishing, being in a pageant, quantum physics, ordinal numbers and caring for and showing a cow at the fair through the presentations of their classmates. “I am so proud of all the students, as many of them experienced public speaking for the first time,” said Mrs. Hamilton.

post_text:
During the months of November and December, the Addison High School Red Cross Club purchased and collected new items for the Net Shelter for Domestic Abuse victims in the Corning and Bath areas. More than nine boxes of hygiene and household cleaning items were collected to donate to this worthwhile cause. From Tide, to toothbrushes, to towels, the students learned a valuable lesson to help others. They also realized the importance of some of these items that we use daily and how we take them being available to us for granted. Besides the items, gift cards were also purchased to help with purchasing gas for cars for these victims to get to and from work.
We appreciate any and all who donated and hope our donations helped others have a more enjoyable Christmas.

shared_text:
Tuscarora Elementary School
November 25, 2019 at 10:05 AM ·

Have you ever read on the school bus? Well, now you can! The School Bus Book Bag Project will now give our students the opportunity to read books on the bus to and from school. Each school bus has their own book bag that has been stocked with books for our students to use during their time on the bus. Our goal for this project is to help give our students just one more place that they can pick up a book and continue to foster their love of reading!

Mrs. Wheeler's class helped to deliver the book bags to the bus garage on Thursday!

"Reading gives us someplace to go when we have to stay where we are." -Mason Cooley

post_text:
The Addison Central School District Board of Education recognized Mr. Ron White at this week's board meeting.

For the last 25 years, Mr. White has honored the memory of his parents through the yearly presentation of the Donald & Marian E. White Citizenship Award. This award recognizes a Tuscarora Elementary student's individual demonstration of exemplary characteristics, behaviors and values of good citizenship.

Our students and school community are so grateful for the continued generosity of Mr. White and his support for our school in the work of promoting positive behavior and good citizenship.

Pictured below are Mr. Ron White, BOE President Mrs. Michelle Terwilliger, former Tuscarora Principal Mrs. Deb Flint and current Tuscarora Principal Mrs. Georgia Weed.

Students overcame fears, made new friends and were excellent ambassadors for our community.

March 14 marks Pi Day, when the symbol used in mathematics to represent a constant is celebrated around the world. Addison Middle School seventh and eighth grade students joined in the celebration with sweet treats and fun. Board of Education member Jim Mitchell and Food Service Assistant Manager Julie Mitchell served a variety of pies to students. The afternoon included Pi-related activities and concluded with the main event, when two teachers who were voted on by students received a pie to the face. Mrs. Guinnip and Mr. Howard, math teachers who organized the event, also volunteered for pies in the face. Students with top averages in their math class earned the opportunity to do the “pie-ing.”

shared_text:
Addison High School
March 26, 2019 at 5:00 PM ·

Seniors at Addison High School recently got a reality check about life after graduation, thanks to a program presented by Corning Credit Union and coordinated by the GST BOCES Career Development Council. “Mad City Money,” a simulation for high schools students, teaches basic money management in a safe, fun setting.

Participants are paired up for a realistic experience with managing a household budget. They must decide their priorities and rotate through stations to purchase housing, transportation, food, clothing, household necessities, daycare and other needs. The simulation also includes tempting “extras” stations, including a mall featuring televisions and video games and a “Fun Stuff” station where students can purchase vacations and entertainment activities. Some participants encounter the “Fickle Finger of Fate” when they are randomly presented with a life situation that may result in a financial setback. The simulation gives students the opportunity to experience the impact of their financial decisions and learn important lessons about budgeting.

Addison Middle School

Our recent STEAM Fair featured a Middle School science fair and displays from both Middle School and High School classes. Participants in the science fair included students in the 8th grade accelerated science class as well as other volunteers.
The science fair judges were a team of science teachers from both the Middle School and High School. Students’ scores determined their award level (first, second, third or participant). There was a points range for each award, so more than one person could place at each level. Students received a certificate and a ribbon for their placement.
Students who placed first and second will move on to the Regional Fair at Alfred State College on March 22.

Addison Middle School
January 28, 2019 at 2:24 PM ·

At the Addison Middle School, it is a priority to foster positive leadership skills in students. We saw that in action last week when the 7th Grade Peer Leaders organized and facilitated the “Be a Buddy, Not a Bully” assembly, with the assistance of the Elmira Enforcers.

Goalie Blake Scott and Defenseman Ondrej Gabrhelik, along with team mascot Captain K-9 and Director of Community Relations Joe Ruggiero, visited the Middle School to discuss how to be a buddy and to share an opportunity for students to earn tickets to the Enforcers’ February 1 home game. Students who sign the “Be a Buddy, Not a Bully” form pledge to be kind to others, speak up when they see bullying, appreciate differences in others and be a buddy to those in need. Each student who signs the form and turns it in at school will receive one free ticket to the game. Additional tickets for family members can be purchased through the school at a discounted price.

Students who sign up will be recognized at the game and the 7th Grade Peer Leaders will sit on the team bench during warm-ups.
